{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Crak!-Lichtenstein.jpg | backcolor= | painting_alignment= | image_size=250px | title=Crak! | artist=[[Roy Lichtenstein]] | year=1963 | medium=[[Lithograph]] | movement=[[Pop art]] | height_metric =48.9 | width_metric =70.2 | height_imperial =19.25 | width_imperial =27.625 | city= | museum=}} '''''Crak!''''' (sometimes '''''Crack!''''') is a 1963 [[pop art]] [[lithograph]] by [[Roy Lichtenstein]] in his [[comic book]] style of using [[Ben-Day dots]] and a [[text balloon]]. It was used in marketing materials for one of Lichtenstein's early shows. It is one of several of his works related to [[military art]] and monocular vision.
== Background == [[File:Crak! source.jpg|upright|thumb|left|The source of ''Crak!'' is a story from ''[[Star Spangled War Stories]]'' #102<!--, written by [[Bob Haney]] and illustrated by [[Jack Abel]]-->. © April–May 1962, National Periodical Publications (DC).]] When Lichtenstein had his first solo show at The [[Leo Castelli Gallery]] in New York City in February 1962, it sold out before opening. The exhibition included ''[[Engagement Ring (Roy Lichtenstein)|Engagement Ring]]'', ''[[Blam (Roy Lichtenstein)|Blam]]'' and ''The Refrigerator''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roy Lichtenstein: Mural With Blue Brushstroke|author=Tomkins, Calvin|isbn=0-8109-2356-4|page=25|year=1988|publisher=[[Harry N. Abrams, Inc.]]|quote=}}</ref> The show ran from February 10 through March 3, 1962. After a west coast exhibition at [[Ferus Gallery]] in Los Angeles from April 1–27, 1963, Lichtenstein had his second solo exhibition at the [[Leo Castelli]] Gallery from September 28&nbsp;– October 24, 1963 that included ''[[Whaam!]]'', ''[[Drowning Girl]]'', ''[[Torpedo...Los!]]'', ''[[Baseball Manager]]'', ''[[In the Car]]'', and ''Conversation''.<ref name=RLOF4>{{cite book|title=Roy Lichtenstein: October Files|editor=Bader, Graham|publisher=[[The MIT Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-262-01258-4|page=2-4|chapter=Reviews 1962–64|author=Judd, Donald|quote=}}</ref><ref name=C>{{cite web|url=http://www.lichtensteinfoundation.org/lfchron1.htm|title=Chronology|accessdate=June 9, 2013|publisher=Roy Lichtenstein Foundation|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606071341/http://lichtensteinfoundation.org/lfchron1.htm|archivedate=June 6, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
Named for its [[onomatopoeic]] graphic text, ''Crak!'' is an offset lithograph on lightweight, white wove paper.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://image-duplicator.com/main.php?work_id=3783&year=1963&decade=60|title=CRAK!|accessdate=June 26, 2013|publisher=LichtensteinFoundation.org}}</ref> According to the Lichtenstein Foundation, it was a marketing poster that "was published to announce Lichtenstein's exhibition at Leo Castelli Gallery, September 28 [&ndash;] October 24, 1963." The foundation notes that the work is sometimes dated 1964 with numbered impressions that are inscribed reflecting that date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://image-duplicator.com/search.php?string=Crak&search_year=&search_series=|title=Search Result: CRAK!|accessdate=June 26, 2013|publisher=LichtensteinFoundation.org}}</ref>
[[File:Roy Lichtenstein.jpg|thumb|upright|Lichtenstein in 1967]] The [[Screen printing|screen-printed]] poster image presents a [[beret]]-clad woman shooting a rifle. Lichtenstein recomposed the comic book source — from a story written by [[Bob Haney]] and illustrated by [[Jack Abel]]<ref>[http://www.comics.org/issue/16867/ "The Town That Wouldn't Die!",] ''Star Spangled War Stories'' #102 credits, Grand Comics Database. Accessed July 3, 2014.</ref> in ''[[Star Spangled War Stories]]'' #102 (Apr./May 1962) — by replacing the mound of sand with what seems to be a stack of [[sandbag]]s. He also isolated the figure by cropping the foreground and background elements.<ref name=RLGB>{{cite book|title=Roy Lichtenstein|editor=Bader, Graham|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-262-01258-4|chapter=Technology Envisioned: Lichtenstein's Monocularity|author=Lobel, Michael|pages=118&ndash;20}}</ref>
Monocular vision is the motif in which the subject is "depicted frontally in such a way as to expose both eyes to the viewer, yet which has one eye closed or otherwise obscured" and not those in which the subject is depicted in profile.<ref>{{cite book|title=Roy Lichtenstein|editor=Bader, Graham|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-262-01258-4|chapter=Footnote 32|author=Lobel, Michael|page=129}}</ref> The main subject has one eye opened and one eye closed, which relates to a pervasive theme of monocularity in Lichtenstein's art with works such as ''[[Torpedo...Los!]]'' and ''[[I Can See the Whole Room...and There's Nobody in It!]]''. The work also is related to Lichtenstein's theme of "machine and embodied vision" as exhibited in works such as ''[[Okay Hot-Shot, Okay!]]'', ''[[Bratatat!]]'', and ''[[Jet Pilot (Roy Lichtenstein)|Jet Pilot]]''.<ref name=RLGB/>
